7.0. Introduction : Univariate & Bivariate Analysis¶

Data in statistics is sometimes classified according to how many variables are in a particular study. Depending on the number of variables being looked at, the data might be univariate, bivariate or multivariate.

Univariate Analysis :¶

When you conduct a study that looks at a single variable, that study involves univariate data. The example of a univariate data can be considering only height of students in the dataset for study. Univariate analysis is the analysis of one (uni) variable. The analysis of univariate data is thus the simplest form of analysis since the information deals with only one quantity that changes. It does not deal with causes or relationships and the main purpose of the analysis is to describe the data and find patterns that exist within it. Some common tools used in Univariate Analysis are measures of central tendencies, measures of dispersion, frequency distributions, bar plot, histogram, pie chart, box-and-whisker plot.

Bivariate Analysis :¶

Bivariate data is when you are studying two variables. Example of bivariate data can be Height and Weight of students in a class. Bivariate analysis is the analysis of exactly two variables. The analysis of this type of data deals with causes and relationships and the analysis is done to find out the relationship among the two variables. Some common tools used in Bivariate Analysis are Correlation Coefficients, Regression Analysis, Scatter plots.

Multivariate analysis is the analysis of more than two variables. It is similar to bivariate but contains more than one dependent variable. The ways to perform analysis on this data depends on the goals to be achieved.

There may be complex and unknown relationships between the variables in your dataset. It is important to discover and quantify the degree to which variables in your dataset are dependent upon each other. This knowledge can help you better prepare your data to meet the expectations of machine learning algorithms, such as linear regression, whose performance will degrade with the presence of these interdependencies.

7.1. Scatter Plots¶

The most basic way to study relationships between two variables is to use a graph and try to look at the overall pattern and study the deviations from the pattern. A scatterplot is one of the most effective ways of studying the relationship between the graphs. It shows the relationship between two quantitative variables measured on the same observations.

Below is a dataset that contains the hours spent studying and test scores ten individuals.

We are interested in the relationship between the two variables. How is one affected by changes in the other?

Lets plot a scatter plot in search of the answer to this question.

In [1]:
# building dataset
study_hrs =  [9,  7, 4, 5, 5, 8, 8, 9, 5, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 6, 7, 6, 6, 4, 3, 5, 5, 6, 7, 7, 7, 6]
test_score = [70,89,84,77,77,87,84,92,78,60,62,75,80,78,68,73,72,69,67,63,65,68,82,75,80,76,73]

#scatter plot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.scatter(study_hrs,test_score)
plt.xlabel('Hours of Study')
plt.ylabel('Test Score')
plt.show()

At first glance, we can see why we call this a scatter diagram. The pattern of points results because each pair of data from the table above has been recorded as a single point. When we view all these points together, we can visualize the relationship that exists between the two variables.

You can see that there is a slight upward trend in the data. That is, those that study more tend to do better.

Scatterplots are useful for identifying general trends in the data as well as identifying points that do not follow the patterns as those data points are always interesting too. For instance, what might one say about Jan, who studied for 9 hours but only received a 70 on the exam? or James, who studied for 4 hours but received 84 ? That would be a data point worth further exploring.

Scatterplots are usually studied on three points : the form, direction, and the strength of the association.

For instance is the form linear or curved? Or is there no pattern at all? In the scatterplot of Hours of Study and Test Score, there is a slight linear pattern. The direction of the plot is also important. Is it positive, negative or is there no direction at all? Our plot above shows a slight positive direction. Lastly, the scatterplot measures the strength of the relationship. How closely do the points fit the form.

Let us take a different example and identify the form, direction, and strength of the relationship between two other measures: Height and Weight.

In [3]:
#self made data
height = [ 67, 72, 77, 74, 69, 70, 71, 72, 74, 76, 75, 73, 68] #inches
weight = [155,188,220,195,175,178,182,180,200,210,210,195,170] #pounds

#scatter plot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.scatter(height,weight)
plt.xlabel('Height (in inches)')
plt.ylabel('Weight (in pounds)')
plt.show()

The form of the relationship is linear for the most part. There are no curves in the plot and there is a clear pattern. The direction is positive; as Height go up, the Weight tends to rise as well. The strength of the relationship is quite strong.

Patterns of Data in Scatterplots¶

Scatterplots are used to analyze patterns in bivariate data. These patterns are described in terms of linearity, slope, and strength.

  • Linearity refers to whether a data pattern is linear (straight) or nonlinear (curved).

  • Slope refers to the direction of change in variable Y when variable X gets bigger. If variable Y also increases, the slope is positive; but if variable Y decreases, the slope is negative.

  • Strength refers to the degree of "scatter" in the plot. If the dots are widely spread, the relationship between variables is weak. If the dots are concentrated around a line, the relationship is strong.

Additionally, scatterplots can reveal unusual features in data sets, such as clusters, gaps, and outliers. The scatterplots below illustrate some common patterns.

**NOTE:** The pattern in the last example (nonlinear, zero slope, weak) is the pattern that is found when two variables are not related.

7.2. Correlation¶

In the previous example of Height vs Weight, we concluded that "The strength of the relationship between Height and Weight is quite strong." Quite strong however is a qualitative term that we have selected to describe the strength of the relationship based on our judgment. What would be ideal is to have a statistic, or some quantitative measure, to measure the strength of the relationship.

In this section, you will discover a statistical measure called Correlation to quantify the strength of the relationship .

Because visual examinations are largely subjective, we need a more precise and objective measure to define the correlation between the two variables. If the two variables are normally distributed, the standard measure of determining the correlation coefficient, often called Pearsons Coefficient of Correlation, is

$$r =\frac{ \sum_{i=1}^{n}(X_i-\bar{X})(Y_i-\bar{Y}) }{% \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(X_i-\bar{X})^2}\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(Y_i-\bar{Y})^2}}$$

The population correlation coefficient is,

$$ \rho = \frac{Cov(X,Y)}{\sigma_X \sigma_Y}$$

where,

$Cov(X,Y) = E[(X-\mu_X)(Y-\mu_Y)]$, is the covariance.

$\sigma_X$ is the standard deviation and $\mu_X$ is the population mean of X

$\sigma_Y$ is the standard deviation and $\mu_Y$ is the population mean of Y

Due to this form, Pearson's Correlation Coefficient is also called Product Moment correlation coefficient.

Covariance¶

Covariance is a measure of the tendency of two variables to vary together. If we have two series, $X$ and $Y$ , their deviations from the mean are $(x_i-\bar x)$ and $(y_i-\bar y)$ respectively. Where $\bar x$ is the sample mean of $X$ and $\bar y$ is the sample mean of $Y$ . Thus,

If $X$ and $Y$ vary together, their deviations tend to have the same sign.

If we multiply them together, the product is positive when the deviations have the same sign and negative when they have the opposite sign. So adding up the products gives a measure of the tendency to vary together.

Covariance is the mean of these products:

$$Cov(X,Y)={1 \over n}{ \sum_{i=1}^{n}(X_i-\bar{X})(Y_i-\bar{Y}) }$$

Covariance is useful in some computations, but it is rarely reported as a summary statistic because it is hard to interpret. Among other problems, its units are the product of the units of $X$ and $Y$ . For example, the covariance of weight and height will be in kilogram-centimeters.

One solution to this problem is to divide the deviations by the standard deviation, i.e., $\frac {(X_i-\bar{X})}{\sigma_X}$ and $\frac {(Y_i-\bar{Y})}{\sigma_Y}$ which yields standard scores, and compute the product of standard scores i.e.,

$$\rho = {1 \over n }{ \sum_{i=1}^{n}{\frac {(X_i-\bar{X})}{\sigma_X}}{\frac {(Y_i-\bar{Y})}{\sigma_Y}} }$$$$\rho = \frac {Cov(X,Y)} {\sigma_X \sigma_Y}$$

This value is called Pearson's correlation. It is easy to compute and easy to interpret. Because standard scores are dimensionless, so is $\rho$.

Before we get into examples, there are several facts about correlation worth pointing out:

  • The correlation measures the strength and direction of a linear relationship between two quantitative variables.

  • A correlation could be positive, meaning both variables move in the same direction, or negative, meaning that when one variable's value increases, the other variables' values decrease. Correlation can also be neural or zero, meaning that the variables are unrelated.

    • Positive Correlation: Both variables change in the same direction.

    • Neutral Correlation: No relationship in the change of the variables.

    • Negative Correlation: Variables change in opposite directions.

  • The correlation is always between -1 and +1.

  • $r = 1$ indicates a perfect positive correlation, $r = -1$ indicates a perfect negative correlation and $r = 0$ indicates that there is no relationship between the different variables.

  • The correlation between $X$ and $Y$ is the same as the correlation between $Y$ and $X$.

Correlation is best used in variables that demonstrate a linear relationship between each other. The fit of the data can be visually represented in a scatterplot. Using a scatterplot, we can generally assess the relationship between the variables and determine whether they are correlated or not.

CAUTION :

The correlation coefficient only measures linear correlations (if x goes up, then y generally goes up/down). It may completely miss out on nonlinear relationships (e.g., if x is close to zero then y generally goes up). Note how all the plots of the bottom row have a correlation coefficient equal to zero despite the fact that their axes are clearly not independent: these are examples of nonlinear relationships. Also, the second row shows examples where the correlation coefficient is equal to 1 or 1; notice that this has nothing to do with the slope.

### Correlation does not imply Causation !! Causation means one event is the result of the occurrence of the other event; i.e. there is a causal relationship between the two events. This is also referred to as cause and effect. Simply because we observe a relationship between two variables in a scatter plot or getting a significant $r$ does not always mean that changes in one variable are responsible for changes in the other. This gives rise to the common phrase in statistics that "correlation does not imply causation". It simply means that, because two things correlate does not necessarily mean that one causes the other. As an example, just because a scatter plot shows people in the UK tend to spend more in the shops when it's cold (or Temp. decreases) doesn't mean cold weather causes frenzied high-street spending. A more plausible explanation would be that cold weather tends to coincide with Christmas and the new year sales.

The pearsonr() function from SciPy can be used to calculate the Pearsons correlation coefficient between two data samples with the same length.

NOTE : This approach uses Python unpacking due to the fact that pearsonr() returns a tuple of two results.

In [4]:
#data
height = [ 67, 72, 77, 74, 69, 70, 71, 72, 74, 76, 75, 73, 68] #inches
weight = [155,188,220,195,175,178,182,180,200,210,210,195,170] #pounds

#computing Pearson's Correlation Coefficient
from scipy.stats import pearsonr

corr, _ = pearsonr(height, weight)
print('Pearsons correlation:', corr)

Pearsons correlation: 0.9768736008473002

We can see that the two variables are positively correlated and that the correlation is 0.977. This suggests a very high level of correlation as it is a value above 0.5 and close to 1.0.

corrcoef() from numpy returns the correlation matrix, which is a two-dimensional array with the correlation coefficients.

In [5]:
import numpy as np

corr_mat = np.corrcoef(height,weight)
print(corr_mat)

[[1.        0.9768736]
 [0.9768736 1.       ]]

Heres a simplified version of the correlation matrix you just created:

Height Weight
Height 1 0.9768736
Weight 0.9768736 1

Clearly we are getting a very high correlation as the data is made-up for illustration purpose only. Lets try to work around a real life data, where we will also see how to explore relationship between variables in a data frame.

corr, _ = pearsonr(dt['Height'], dt['Weight'])

Pearsons correlation: 0.7

So from real life data it is confirmed that there is a strong positive relation between Height and Weight.

A correlation matrix can be used for this purpose. .corr() function from pandas library returns a Correlation Matrix of all numeric variables present in a data frame.

Observe that the diagonal of correlation matrix is 1 as it represent self correlation of variables. Also observe that the values of correlation coefficient for either side of the diagonal (Upper Triangle and Lower Triangle) of the correlation matrix are equal (mirror images) of each other. Recall the statement, "The correlation between $X$ and $Y$ is the same as the correlation between $Y$ and $X$."

As you can observe, the correlation matrix in case of many variables is dificult to interpret as well as not very pleasent to eyes. Lets try to visulaize this correlation matrix using Heatmap plot.

Plotting a heatmap is a piece of cake, thanks to seaborn library.

For more info about heatmap visit: https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.heatmap.html

In [20]:
#Plotting a Correlation Matrix using Heatmap

correlation = wine.corr() #compute correlation for all features in dataset

#plotting 
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))  # set figure size
sns.heatmap(correlation, annot=True, linewidths=0, vmin=-1, vmax = +1, cmap="RdBu_r")
plt.show()
In [21]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

#Plotting a diagonal correlation matrix

correlation = wine.corr()  #compute correlation for all features in dataset
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8)) # set figure size

# Generate a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(correlation, dtype=np.bool))
#print(mask)

sns.heatmap(correlation, annot=True, linewidths=0, vmin=-1, vmax = +1, cmap="RdBu_r",mask=mask)
plt.show()
  • np.ones_like : Return an array of ones with the same shape and type as a given array.
  • np.triu: Upper triangle of an array.
